    <title>Combined summary - eltoo: A Simplified update Mechanism for Lightning and Off-Chain Contracts</title>
    <updated>2023-06-02T03:00:09.154216+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2018-May/001229.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Lightning Network, a layer-two scaling solution for Bitcoin, has proposed several updates to improve its efficiency. One such update is the use of SIGHASH_NOINPUT and SIGHASH_ANYONECANPAY for transactions with multiple inputs. Additionally, there have been discussions comparing the Decker-Russell-Osuntokun channels to Poon-Dryja/LN-penalty channels in terms of the number of transactions required.Another significant development in the Lightning Network protocol stack is the adoption of a new update mechanism called eltoo. Eltoo replaces the penalty-based invalidation mechanism currently in use and addresses several issues encountered while specifying and implementing the Lightning Network. However, potential vulnerabilities in the Eltoo protocol have been discovered by Bitcoin developer David A. Harding. These include an attacker stalling a payment channel so long that the transactional fees required to complete it are higher than the value of the channel.Discussions on the SIGHASH_NOINPUT signature hash type proposed for use in the upcoming Eltoo BIP have also taken place between Christian Decker, Dave, ZmnSCPxj, and Russell O'Connor. They also exchanged thoughts on the removal of trigger transactions and the accurate summary of the SIGHASH_NOINPUT paper.Furthermore, email exchanges between Christian Decker, Carsten Strotmann, and ZmnSCPxj covered several topics related to Bitcoin's Script language and the Lightning Network. The group discussed the terminology used in the eltoo paper, suggesting changes to avoid confusion and clarify complex scripts. They also discussed CSV-encumbrance on settlement transactions and its impact on absolute-timelocked contracts transported on the channel. ZmnSCPxj questioned the use of terminology in a paper he received and suggested an adaptive scheme for eltoo's locktime-based sequencing to allow for more updates. The group also discussed the impact of CSV-encumbrance on settlement transactions when carrying contracts in the channel and suggested changes to routing algorithms. Finally, they touched on the use of watchtowers and the need for professional parties that can manage near-100% uptime to safely perform transaction routing.</summary>
